  "text": "# etcd Client gRPC Retry and Timeout Policy Implementation\n\n## Overview\n\nThe etcd client implements a comprehensive client-side retry and timeout policy for gRPC operations in the GitHub repository github.com/etcd-io/etcd. The implementation spans multiple files in the client/v3 package and provides different retry strategies for KV, Watch, and Lease operations.\n\n## Core Components\n\n### 1. gRPC Retry Interceptor (client/v3/retry_interceptor.go)\n\nThe retry interceptor is the main component handling retry logic for both unary and streaming RPCs:\n\n- **unaryClientInterceptor** (line 41): Returns a new retrying unary client interceptor that handles retry for non-streaming calls. It implements:\n  - Automatic retry on transient errors\n  - Exponential backoff with jitter\n  - Token refresh on authentication failures\n  - Peer tracking for debugging\n\n- **streamClientInterceptor** (line 112): Returns a new retrying stream client interceptor for server-side streaming (1:n) calls. It:\n  - Supports retry only for ServerStreams (not ClientStreams or BidiStreams)\n  - Buffers messages to support retry\n  - Reestablishes streams on errors\n\n- **serverStreamingRetryingStream** (line 188): Implements the actual retry logic for streaming responses:\n  - Tracks buffered sends and received messages\n  - Implements RecvMsg with retry capability\n  - Reestablishes stream and resends buffered messages on failure\n\n- **isSafeRetry** (line 330): Determines if a request is safe for retry based on error type and retry policy (repeatable vs nonRepeatable)\n\n- **waitRetryBackoff** (line 312): Handles backoff timing between retries using context-aware waiting\n\n- **backoffLinearWithJitter** (line 446): Creates a backoff function that applies linear backoff with configurable jitter\n\n### 2. Client Connection and Initialization (client/v3/client.go)\n\nThe main client handles connection setup with integrated retry policies:\n\n- **newClient** (line 408): Initializes the client with:\n  - Connection establishment via dialWithBalancer\n  - Integration of retry interceptors\n  - Health check via waitForConnection\n  - Token/authentication setup\n\n- **dialSetupOpts** (line 229): Configures dial options including:\n  - Keepalive parameters (DialKeepAliveTime, DialKeepAliveTimeout)\n  - Unary and stream retry interceptors with configurable limits and backoff\n  - Default: 100 max unary retries with 25ms backoff and 10% jitter\n\n- **waitForConnection** (line 345): Performs health check on the gRPC connection using gRPC health service:\n  - Uses grpc.WaitForReady(true) for robust checking\n  - Handles Unimplemented and FailedPrecondition gracefully\n  - Validates connection is ready before returning\n\n- **roundRobinQuorumBackoff** (line 537): Implements round-robin aware backoff strategy:\n  - Applies backoff only after cycling through the quorum\n  - Uses jitterUp function to add randomness\n  - Optimizes retry efficiency in multi-endpoint scenarios\n\n### 3. Safe Retry Logic (client/v3/retry.go)\n\nThe retry module distinguishes between safe retry scenarios for different RPC types:\n\n- **isSafeRetryImmutableRPC** (line 54): For immutable requests (e.g., Get, Range):\n  - Safe to retry on Unavailable errors\n  - Not safe for other server errors (e.g., ErrCompacted)\n  - Retries on transient connection failures\n\n- **isSafeRetryMutableRPC** (line 85): For mutable requests (e.g., Put, Delete, Txn):\n  - Only safe to retry on Unavailable when no connection is established\n  - Protects write-at-most-once semantics\n  - Checks for specific error descriptions indicating no available addresses\n\n- **RetryKVClient** (line 101): Wraps KV client operations with appropriate retry policies:\n  - Range/Get: repeatable policy (safe to retry)\n  - Put/Delete/Txn: nonRepeatable policy (restricted retry)\n\n- **RetryLeaseClient** (line 132): Wraps Lease client operations:\n  - LeaseGrant: repeatable policy\n  - LeaseKeepAlive: repeatable policy (for stream retry)\n  - LeaseRevoke/LeaseTimeToLive: repeatable policy\n\n### 4. KV Operations (client/v3/kv.go)\n\nThe KV interface defines core operations:\n\n- **Put** (line 39): Stores key-value pairs with gRPC call options from client\n- **Get** (line 49): Retrieves values with optional range, revision, limit, and sort options\n- **Delete** (line 52): Deletes keys with optional range support\n- **Txn** (line 65): Creates transactions for atomic multi-operation requests\n\nAll KV operations use the client's call options which include retry configuration.\n\n### 5. Watch Implementation (client/v3/watch.go)\n\nWatch provides long-lived streaming connections with intelligent retry:\n\n- **watchGRPCStream** (line 157): Manages a single gRPC streaming connection:\n  - Tracks all active watchers on the stream\n  - Handles stream reconnection and watcher resumption\n  - Implements buffering for watch responses (respc channel)\n  - Manages closing and error handling\n\n- **newWatcherGRPCStream** (line 275): Creates a new watch stream with:\n  - Context wrapping using valCtx for non-cancellable context (line 276)\n  - Automatic stream lifecycle management\n  - Separation of request/response channels for concurrency\n\n- **valCtx** (line 269): A custom context wrapper that:\n  - Preserves context values\n  - Never returns Done(), allowing watches to continue indefinitely\n  - Returns a zero-time deadline and nil error to prevent cancellation\n\n- **Watch** (line 298): Initiates a watch with:\n  - Request queuing to the watch stream\n  - Automatic ID assignment for watch requests\n  - Streaming response handling through watch channels\n\nWatch streams use the stream retry interceptor configuration (disabled by default but safe to enable individually).\n\n### 6. Lease Keep-Alive (client/v3/lease.go)\n\nLease management with continuous renewal:\n\n- **lessor** (line 151): Manages lease keep-alive streams:\n  - Tracks active keep-alives for multiple leases\n  - Implements automatic renewal via keep-alive loop\n  - Handles stream reconnection with backoff\n  - Uses retryConnWait (500ms) between reconnection attempts\n\n- **KeepAlive** (line 273): Establishes automatic lease renewal:\n  - Creates a channel for keep-alive responses\n  - Multiplexes multiple subscribers to the same lease\n  - Implements deadline tracking for keep-alive deadlines\n  - Uses defaultTTL (5 seconds) before actual TTL is known\n\n- **NewLease** (line 192): Creates a lease client with:\n  - RetryLeaseClient wrapping for safe retry\n  - KeepAliveTimeout = DialTimeout + 1 second\n\n### 7. Configuration (client/v3/config.go, client/v3/options.go)\n\nConfigurable retry and timeout parameters:\n\n- **Config.DialTimeout**: Timeout for establishing connection (default: configurable)\n- **Config.DialKeepAliveTime**: Keepalive ping interval (default: configurable)\n- **Config.DialKeepAliveTimeout**: Keepalive response timeout (default: configurable)\n- **Config.MaxUnaryRetries**: Maximum unary retries (default: 100 via options.go line 45)\n- **Config.BackoffWaitBetween**: Base backoff duration (default: 25ms via options.go line 53)\n- **Config.BackoffJitterFraction**: Jitter percentage (default: 0.10 or 10% via options.go line 56)\n- **Config.PermitWithoutStream**: Allow keepalive without active streams\n\n### 8. Utility Functions\n\n- **jitterUp** (client/v3/utils.go line 28): Applies random jitter to backoff duration:\n  - Adds/subtracts time within jitter fraction\n  - Example: 10s with 0.1 jitter returns time in [9s, 11s]\n  - Uses cryptographic rand for unpredictability\n\n- **WithRequireLeader** (client/v3/ctx.go line 28): Adds metadata requiring cluster leader:\n  - Ensures requests fail if no leader is available\n  - Prevents watch streams from getting stuck on partitioned nodes\n\n### 9. Endpoint Management\n\n- **EtcdManualResolver** (client/v3/internal/resolver/resolver.go line 31): gRPC resolver for endpoint management:\n  - Maintains list of endpoints and pro